04817nam a22006015i 9782766302543DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20242024xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97827663025437 a10.1515/97827663025432doi  a(DE-B1597)678663  a(OCoLC)1419789044  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aMED0500002bisacsh1 aCollectif, Collectif, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRobots and Gadgets :bAging at Home /cCollectif Collectif; ed. by Félix Pageau, Emilian Mihailov, Tenzin Wangmo. 1aQuébec : bPresses de l'Université Laval, c[2024] 4c©2024  a1 online resource (132 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tTable of Contents -- tIntroduction -- tArtificial Intelligence: A Brief Introduction for Non-Experts on the Technological Advances That Are Bringing Smart Devices into Our Lives -- tEthical Perspectives on Dementia, the Person, and Artificial Intelligence, with Special Reference to the Dementia-Care Enterprise in Switzerland: Critical Reflections, with Caveats, from the United States -- tEthical Issues Related to Smart Technologies and Artificial Intelligence -- tSmart-Home Technology in the Care of Older Persons: Deciphering Privacy Concerns -- tIs the House of Smart Technologies Less Human? Challenges to Human Dignity in the Care of Older Persons -- tConclusion -- tContributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe aging of the world’s population has brought with it a set of challenges. Baby boomers in the Western world, who have lived through several cycles of change, are about to experience another transformation — the automation of in-home geriatric care. Equipping a home with interconnected gadgets and with robots that incorporate artificial intelligence seems increasingly possible. Such devices, connected to a wireless network and the Internet, can observe, communicate, and also assist caregivers, providing support to an elderly person as they age in their own home. These technologies have the potential to improve care for those suffering from various maladies, including dementia. Seniors may be more accepting of robots and gadgets if such devices enable them to remain in their home despite deficits related to aging. However, as bioethics has often demonstrated, it is important to critically analyze the implications of using these devices, as is proposed in this book.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aMEDICAL / Ethics.2bisacsh  aArtificial intelligence, AI, non-expert, smart device, gadgets, aging, ethical perspectives, ethical issues, smart-technologies, smart home technology, human care, older persons, privacy, human dignity.1 aElger, Bernice S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcLean, Athena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMihailov, Emilian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMihailov, Emilian, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPageau, Félix, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPageau, Félix, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aTian, Yi Jiao, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWangmo, Tenzin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWangmo, Tenzin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aYadava, Koshika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZenke, Friedemann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311140848440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9782766302543?locatt=m